docs.abstract: What can be done about all of the suffering that remains?
docs.snippet: What can be done about all of the suffering that remains?
docs.lead_paragraph: After a wretched and withering year that didn’t so much pass by as scorch through, the guilty verdict in Derek Chauvin’s trial for the murder of George Floyd arrived as a relief. It’s been a long time since it felt as though Americans had the luxury of thinking about the future we want to live in, as opposed to putting out fires in an endless present. In so many respects, we were due for a little hope.

headline.main: Chauvin Was Convicted. Something Is Still Very Wrong.
headline.print_headline: Chauvin Was Convicted, but Suffering Remains

docs.abstract: Officer Patricia Lio of the Milton Police Department in Massachusetts is accused of berating her son’s 14-year-old Black friend about his stance on the Black Lives Matter movement.
docs.snippet: Officer Patricia Lio of the Milton Police Department in Massachusetts is accused of berating her son’s 14-year-old Black friend about his stance on the Black Lives Matter movement.
docs.lead_paragraph: A white Massachusetts police officer will face criminal charges in connection with an off-duty episode in which she is accused of berating a Black teenager, a friend of her son, over his support of the Black Lives Matter movement, a court official ruled this week.

headline.main: White Police Officer to Face Charge She Intimidated Son’s Black Friend

docs.lead_paragraph: By the time George Floyd died in May, Leslie Redmond was a veteran of protests in Minneapolis. In 2015, she was one of the people who occupied a police precinct for 18 days. In 2020, she was the leader of the local chapter of the N.A.A.C.P., organizing marches and meeting with community leaders.

headline.main: ‘I constantly get emotional.’ After a year of protests, Minneapolis activists await justice.

docs.abstract: The inquiry will likely lead to a consent decree between the department and the federal government, a tool that the Obama administration repeatedly used to address police misconduct.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Justice Department will investigate the policies and operations of the Minneapolis Police Department, Attorney General Merrick B. Garland announced on Wednesday, a day after the former officer Derek Chauvin was convicted of murder in the death of George Floyd in a rare rebuke of police violence.

headline.main: Attorney General Merrick Garland announces an investigation into the Minneapolis Police Department.

docs.lead_paragraph: MINNEAPOLIS — In a trial where many key figures have spent hours on the stand, the prosecution whipped through one of their most anticipated witnesses, the doctor who performed George Floyd’s official autopsy, in a mere 50 minutes on Friday.

headline.main: Despite Other Factors, Police Caused Floyd’s Death, Medical Examiner Says

docs.lead_paragraph: After three weeks of testimony from 45 witnesses, the lawyers gave their concluding arguments on Monday in the trial of Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer charged with murdering George Floyd.

headline.main: Takeaways from the closing arguments of the Derek Chauvin trial.

docs.abstract: George Floyd used it to buy cigarettes, but a store clerk thought it was fake. Neither side in the trial has spent much time addressing it.
docs.snippet: George Floyd used it to buy cigarettes, but a store clerk thought it was fake. Neither side in the trial has spent much time addressing it.
docs.lead_paragraph: The last three weeks of the Derek Chauvin trial provided jurors with a comprehensive understanding of George Floyd’s final moments, pieced together from hours of video and witness testimony. But there is one part of the case that lawyers for both sides have spent little time on: the $20 bill that brought the police to the scene in the first place.

headline.main: Little has been said about the $20 bill that brought officers to the scene.
headline.print_headline: Gone All but Unnoticed: The $20 Bill That Brought Officers to the Scene

byline.original: By Nicholas Bogel-Burroughs and Will Wright

docs.abstract: George Floyd’s struggle to breathe while under Mr. Chauvin’s knee has become a major discussion during testimony.
docs.snippet: George Floyd’s struggle to breathe while under Mr. Chauvin’s knee has become a major discussion during testimony.
docs.lead_paragraph: The trial of the former officer Derek Chauvin will end its second week on Friday after testimony from several witnesses about George Floyd’s precise cause of death. Mr. Floyd was pinned to the ground for more than nine minutes by Mr. Chauvin’s knee; prosecutors are arguing that he died from asphyxia, while the defense says that drugs in his system may be the cause.

headline.main: Key Moments on Day 10 of the Derek Chauvin Trial

byline.original: By Will Wright, Shaila Dewan, Nicholas Bogel-Burroughs, John Eligon and Julie Bosman

docs.abstract: Mr. Chauvin invoked his Fifth Amendment right not to testify in his own defense. With testimony concluded, the case will go to the jury on Monday.
docs.snippet: Mr. Chauvin invoked his Fifth Amendment right not to testify in his own defense. With testimony concluded, the case will go to the jury on Monday.
docs.lead_paragraph: The prosecution and the defense rested their cases in the trial of Derek Chauvin on Thursday, bringing an end to testimony, which in recent days has focused on attempts by Mr. Chauvin’s lawyers to convince  jurors that George Floyd was not killed by Mr. Chauvin’s actions.

headline.main: Key Moments on Day 14 of the Derek Chauvin Trial
